One of the biggest struggles within my own business and having the amazing women that join #JESSIESGIRLS is…

KEEPING THEM…

⚠️ CHANGING YOUR PHYSIQUE AND HEALTH TAKES TIME ⚠️

If you’re just starting a fitness journey (or coming back to it after taking a lot of time off), you’ll see results fast simply by lifting weights consistently, BUT…

You’re going to have to be consistent for YEARS before seeing a serious increase in muscle growth and strength! (Notice I said years…not weeks or months).

Think about how long it takes to master a skill (or show major improvement) in other areas of life - learning a language, getting a degree, growing your eyebrows back, excelling at a sport, etc…

These things are all very exciting when you see a little bit of improvement in the very beginning…but do they have sticking points and times where you wanted to give up? YES.

What happened when you didn’t give up?…

YOU BECAME GREAT.

Think about something you worked hard at for a long period of time…

Did it require patience? Did it take over a year? Most likely, yes.

DID YOU CHANGE WHAT YOU DID OR HOW YOU DID IT EVERY SINGLE DAY OR WEEK???

I’m guessing NO. You let it be mundane, predictable, routine, ordinary…your new normal. You began celebrating the little wins within those routines, knowing that sticking with the plan and finding consistency was the BIG win in time.

Random, constantly changing workouts can lead to fast growth if you’re just getting started, but I’m here to remind you about the time and work and consistency it’s going to take for lasting change, BIG change, the change that you’ve been obsessing over ever since you decided to change.

Just a reminder to love yourself exactly as you are 🫶🏼 Especially as we start together Monday for 4 transforming weeks.

Along with workouts + macros, these are the other areas we’re working on. I wanted to share my own goals in case it inspires you 😏

💫 Daily Improvement.

1️⃣ 1 glass of wine per night. I reallly enjoy wine at the end of my day but it has become habitual. I’ve gone from enjoying the taste, loving how it compliments food, etc to just pouring that shit into a glass mindlessly.

2️⃣ I’ve been “trying” to wake up earlier. I wake up when my girls wake up and it makes every morning hectic. I’m trying to get myself ready and them ready at the same time in the same hour before we all leave the house. It feels like shit but I keep pressing snooze. I want to wake up before them so that I get ready and then can dedicate the rest of the morning to supporting them.

💫 Practicing Kindness.

I consider myself kind but where I will practice this is while driving LOL. With my hectic mornings (see above), I can get a little ragey 😂 My rage is discreet, like scratching my cheek with my middle finger as they fly by me 🤣💀 but I don’t like how it affects me and sure as heck doesn’t help me get my day started off with kindness. For the next 4 weeks, I will pray for them and smile instead 😇

💫 Time in Nature.

I live in one of the most beautiful places in the world and I can sit my ass inside all day and not go outside 🤦🏼‍♀️Taking Zona for a walk or getting outside and enjoying the outdoors (skiing, snowshoeing, etc) is my goal.

💫 Water.

I’m great during the day but know I can do better. Replacing the wine at night (see above) with water will work wonders.

💫 Personal Development.

I purchase audio books and download podcasts and NEVER listen to them. I’ll be more intentional about playing them for a few minutes each day. Also, I can level up more and do something that helps my social anxiety. There’s so many things I’m interested in but I won’t show up or sign up because my anxiety kicks in. I’ll keep you guys posted 🙏🏼

SO excited to grow with you over the next 4 weeks!!

If you’re feeling off performing hip thrusts, or just not feeling it in your glutes, here are a few simple adjustments 🍑

1️⃣ Your feet may be too far forward - scoop your heels toward your butt and play with your foot position (width, toes pointed out, etc) until you feel your glutes working.

2️⃣ Instead of tipping your head back and looking up during your hip thrusts, keep your chin tucked and your gaze forward, just over the top of your knees throughout the entire movement.

3️⃣ Find a bench that hits just about at the bottom of your shoulder blades when sitting up to it.

Have fun hip thrusting! Leave a comment below with any questions! ⬇️💪🏼

Ladies trying to grow your buns, this one’s for you! Have you heard of B-stance squats? 🍑⬇

Think of B-stance as regular squats with 10x the benefits! They’re great for growing and strengthening the glutes while also helping you with balance!

What’s the proper form?

1️⃣Set your working leg (front leg) up like you would for a regular squat stance. Your knee should be tracking over your toe.
2️⃣The back foot should just be resting on the ground. All your weight should be on that front foot.
3️⃣You can have your back foot turned out in whatever way feels good for you.

Try them out in your next workout and let me know what you think!

The last two mornings I have woken up at 5:30 to do whatever feels good in the moment. I made two rules - don’t lay in bed awake and think 💭 and don’t scroll on my phone. Both of those things make me feel like shit and I do them the most. The first morning I stayed in my bed, still laying down but listened to a meditation app for 10 minutes. Once it finished I sat up tall, legs crossed, one hand on my heart and one on my belly and counted 10 deep breaths - with a 5 second inhale and 8 second exhale. I wrote an affirmation down on an index card a few weeks back and spent some time repeating it in my head. I have a hard time believing my affirmations…even while I’m repeating them to myself thoughts come in telling me it’s bullshit, this isn’t working, etc. I ignore, and continue to repeat. I am still not in a place where my affirmations are changing my life/energy/thoughts but I’m going to stay consistent with it through the negative thoughts and wait for the shift to come. Then I drank a full glass of water next to my bed before heading downstairs for coffee. The second 5:30am morning was today. I woke up feeling anxious. Again, I stayed in bed (it helps to have a peaceful room that you love) with my sunrise lamp (highly recommend), did my 10 breaths and affirmations, then read a few pages out of one of the 3 books and 17 audiobooks I carry around pretending like I’m going to get through one of them. Drank water then headed downstairs to make a cup of coffee to not make my anxiety better 😆 My point here today is - don’t let the perfect “morning routine” and beautiful posts fool you. You can do all the things and still feel like shit and cry at the same time. You can meditate and spend the entire session just trying to keep the negative thoughts away. You can lay in bed awake telling yourself to get up and do the things you know will help you feel better but not be able to move. You can make a strong, yummy cup of coffee even though it doesn’t help your anxiety. All of it is okay. You’re doing great. Keep trying. I love you 💞

✔Drive the elbow behind the body while retracting the shoulder blade.
✔Pull the barbell towards your hip and slowly lower the barbell back to the starting position

Dumbbell exercises>>>

Dumbbells are so versatile and effective and can be used in upper, lower body, and core exercises. The sky’s the limit on your choices of exercises and workouts with these bad boys. 😎

Here are a few of my top exercises using Dumbbells: 

✔Reverse Lunge Deadlift- 
Targets the muscles of the quads, glutes, hamstrings, and hips. It also works the core and upper-back muscles to maintain posture while the lower body moves.

✔Single Arm Row-
A great unilateral exercise that primarily targets your back (and also upper arms and core). These will help you lift and carry more effortlessly even outside of the gym!

✔Squats-
Increases strength and size in your posterior chain muscles, like the hamstrings and glutes. Also works the quadriceps and calves. Get double the benefits of bodyweight squats when you use dumbbells!

Lats get into the correct form of these exercises! 😜

✔V-Grip Lat Pulldown
-Grasp the handle with a neutral grip and initiate the movement by depressing the shoulder blades and then flexing the elbow while extending the shoulder.
-Using your back muscles (avoid trying to pull down with your arm strength), pull the handle towards your body until the elbows are in line with or slightly behind your torso and then, with control, lower the handle back to the starting position under control and repeat the movement. 

✔Seated Cable Row
-Grasp the bar or handles, keeping your legs slightly bent and your back straight. You should be sitting straight upright or with a slight lean forward (whichever works best for you) with your shoulders back to engage your lats. Keeping your body in position, pull the handle toward your lower rib cage.
-Pull your shoulder blades back, squeeze, pause, and then return the weight back to the starting position. Repeat the movement, keeping your back muscles engaged and trying not to pull the weight using your arm strength. 

✔Barbell Z Press
-Start sitting on the floor with the barbell in a front rack position, grip about shoulder width apart, extending your legs straight out in front of you and slightly open.
-Press the weight up to a fully locked position overhead with your head peeking through “the window” between your two arms.
-Shrug your shoulders actively into the ear with the wrist stacked above.
-Slowly lower the weight back to the front rack position and repeat the movement.

It’s a boobs appreciate post. And a farewell. In a couple of hours I go in for surgery to have my implants removed. I’m crying, I’m anxious. But ready.

I got my first breast implants in 2005 when I was 24. I broke up with my fiancé at the time and thought that they would “help” me feel validated and sexy. One of them encapsulated and I had a second surgery.

Fast forward to 38 years old and I had them exchanged for new implants in 2019 because they were 14 years old, I breastfed 2 babies, and they were a hot mess 🌀🌀 And now one of them has actually folded in half 🤯 somehow (see last video where I’m trying to show the fold 😳).

Each time I’ve done something with them, I’ve always done it to “look better” and have that outside validation.

I find myself now, in my 40s, wanting to undo all of that. To rediscover myself. Go back to my most natural version (except my platinum pixie…that’s not going anywhere 😉🧚). Learn how to love my body exactly how it was made for me.

How can I coach women to love themselves when I haven’t TRULY loved my own self? How can I show my two young daughters that they are perfect EXACTLY the way they are when I haven’t felt that myself?

It will be a journey. I’ve wrapped up a big part of my identity in my outside appearance. These boobs are a part of that.

Zero shame in this post. I LOVE boobs ☺️ And I hope you love yours, too, no matter what you’ve got 😍

This is just my own, personal story. So, bye 👋🏼 to these boobs. I’m gonna go take a quick nap and wake up more me than ever before ✨ I love you guys!

Today’s #ootd 😆 Wow…it blows me away how many of you have removed your implants, want to remove them, or are in support of removing them. The stories you’ve shared in my comments and DMs are so real and so validating. I truly had no idea just how many women think about this or experience issues. I’ve seen a lot about breast implant illness over the years and, while that’s not my case, it’s remarkable how many women remove their implants and have some or all symptoms relieved.

Today I’m 3 days post explant and have minimal pain. Any discomfort I have is mostly from the drains (they’ll come out Monday) and being wrapped up tight like this. I took my pain meds the first 2 days but now it has been over 24 hours since I’ve taken anything except Tylenol. The STRANGEST side effect I have right now is my vision is totally blurry. I’m thinking it’s from the anesthesia? I can’t even see a word on my phone without my strongest prescription glasses and holding the phone really far away. It’s a little better today, so I’m thinking it will just go away.

I’ve taken the wrap and compression bra off twice to peek 🫣 and it’s not that upsetting. The scariest part about the explant for me is the unknown…not knowing what they’ll look like. They’re kinda cute…definitely busted up a bit…but cute 😂 The part struggling the most right now are just the areola scars from my past surgeries. My original breast augmentation in 2005, capsulectomy that same year, and my implant exchange in 2019 ALLLL were through the areola. Poor little ladies have been through a lot. Those scars have always been stretched out over my implants and now they just look like they don’t know what to do 🤷🏼‍♀️😂

A lot of you have asked if I had just my implants removed or the capsule and scar tissue, too. I had it all removed. Official name of my surgery is a BILATERAL CAPSULECTOMY WITH EXPLANTATION. I had my surgeon take photos of all of it, maybe I’ll throw those up on my stories. When I look at those pics I just feel disbelief that we put that shit in our bodies. Again, I LOVE boobs…but this is all just so crazy.

Look ma, no drains! I don’t really care what stage of recovery I’m in, having those things out makes me feel 1000000x better. I wasn’t supposed to get them out until this Thursday, but I’ve barely drained anything since Saturday so I got to do it today. They also took the tape off my incisions and snipped my sutures. It feels amazing!

I want to say that there’s barely any pain, but when you’re a woman who has labored for 14 hours unmedicated, had 2 c-sections, breastfed 2 babies, and had Mastitis 1000 times I don’t think I recognize what boob pain is 😂

Swipe to see my incisions and the bruising. This is what it looks like 5 days post explant. Some things I forgot to mention that keep coming up in my DMs is that I had silicone implants ABOVE the muscle. I don’t know how that’s affecting my recovery, but I forgot to mention that and a lot of you have been wondering.

Love sharing this journey with you! Thank you for being open to it and supporting me. I love you! 🍒

Resistance bands are a GREAT addition to add into your leg days 💪🏼

Here are 3 of my favs👇

✔️Banded Pull Through

-Attach the band to a sturdy object at knee level.
-Step into the band and place it right at/below your hip crease.
-Step forward to create quite a bit of tension in the band then begin hinging at the hips.
-Keep your knees in one spot and shins vertical.
-Squeeze your glutes to drive your hips forward.

✔️Lateral Band Walk

-Play with placing the band below or above your knees to see which placement activates your glutes the most.
-Position your feet shoulder-width apart.
-Take an athletic stance with your chest lifted and sit back into your heels.
-Step out laterally, leading with the outside edge of your foot, making sure your knee and ankle stay aligned vertically.

✔️Banded Clamshell

-Lie on your side with your knees slightly bent, one leg on top of the other, and place a resistance band either above or below the knees.
-Keep your knee and ankle aligned while you lift your top leg.
-Keep your hips squared forward, refraining from the top hip rolling backward.

If you ever find yourself unable to use your arms or chest in the gym, here’s a great workout for you! 😆💪🏼

Officially 2 weeks post surgery tomorrow and this has been my one and only workout. I didn’t go heavy at all, and didn’t worry too much about how many sets and reps to complete. I knew I needed to take it easy on my body, not get too sore (healing from the explant is enough recovery for me, thank you 😮‍💨), and didn’t want to rush so that I wouldn’t fall down or something stupid that isn’t worth it.

Some of you were surprised to hear it in one of my recent posts, but I do suffer from severe gym anxiety. I always have, and I still do. So anytime I’m out of the gym for a little while, can’t workout like I usually do, need to make a lot of modifications, I’m wrapped up in an ace bandage, etc…it makes it extremely overwhelming to get to the gym and get through a workout. I’m grateful for Alex and his goofiness and for being my crutch 💜

Here’s what I did ➡️

⚡️Walking Lunges (with pulses/1 1/4 reps) - 3 sets x 15 per side
⚡️Leg Extensions - 4 sets x 15-20 reps
⚡️Seated Leg Curls - 4 sets x 15-20 reps
⚡️Step Ups - 3 sets x 10-15 reps per side
⚡️Hip Abductors - 3 sets x 15-20 reps

I’m feeling great and plan to get another lower body workout in later this week, and then start to get more consistent with those lower body workouts. Upper body is still off the table right now, but I’ll keep you posted! Love you all so much for going on this journey with me 🫶🏼

Some things I learned from my Instagramless summer:

Slowing down is hard. I have always strived to produce and perform and set the bar higher. I learned that it’s not actually who I am. I prefer to go slow and take my time. Month one was uncomfortable…I felt unproductive, anxiety, and shame  for sitting and breathing. Month two I found myself sitting in my chair watching the river flow by thinking…I LIVE HERE NOW 😂 It took a month. But I can truly say I don’t feel a lot of pressure to do things immediately anymore. It remained on my list and was waiting there for me when I did get to it. There was ZERO difference in doing it immediately or in 2-14 days. Hallefuckin'lujah.

I’m doing my best. That has NEVER been good enough for me. I always want to be THE best in other’s eyes. It was always about how others perceived me. I feel I have made huge strides in believing that I am doing my best and that my best is perfectly okay.

Overall, I felt more present than I have ever felt before. I had an incredible time with my baby girls, I truly feel like I gave them all of me 🥹 One of my favorite parts was taking photos of them and all the things we did this summer without having to get the “Instagram picture.” We just took the fucking picture and kept going. I didn’t retake it 500 times, didn’t color edit it, didn’t crop out something bugging me in the background, didn’t write a caption for it, didn’t open Instagram to post it at a high engagement time….NOTHIN. Just fucking smiled and sent it to my mom 😂

Next week will be 4 months post explant. I didn’t get a lift - just removed the breast implants, capsules, and scar tissue. They look amazing with clothes on and I’ve never felt more confident or at home in my own body. I’ll most likely do a lift later on. To me, having them removed was truly a radical act of self-love and a “coming home” to myself. I wasn’t sick from them…I’m just on a journey to find myself and it was my first step. I’m about 6 months post explant this week. This update is probably the most real, since I didn’t end up with great tiny little boobies afterward. I had small B cups naturally, then screwed with them for 20 years, breastfed 2 babies for almost a year each, then took the implants out and was left with some extra skin, asymmetry, and very little (to no) boobies at all. Before I get into the procedure I did today…know that STILL I’d rather be dealing with all of this than have the implants still in. The way I feel, my body feels, and the overall free/comfortable in my skin/confidence I have post explant is indescribable ✨ Okay…here’s what I did today. I have extra skin on the bottom half of my breasts and an A cup on the left and a ZERO cup on the right. My doctor “harvested” (so creepy!) fat on my thighs and injected it into my breasts. Ideally, you’d have plenty of fat to harvest…I don’t…so there’s a great chance that this won’t work at all. He was able to get 150cc’s of fat total from both my right and left outer thighs. That’s very little but it was enough to put about 75cc’s in each breast (average breast implant sizes are between 300-500cc’s). It was an hour long, in-office procedure, totally awake (just numbed the areas). After a procedure like this your body will usually absorb 30-50% of the transferred fat…so in 6 months this could all just go away 😆 I was willing to try this less invasive option before I do a full lift to remove the excess skin. 🍈💋

Last month I went into @bonaldiaesthetics for a VISIA skin analysis. This was so cool! With a fresh, makeup-free face the machine scans your skin and takes images for an in-depth analysis. The purpose of it is to find out where your skin’s strengths and weaknesses are and which skin services and products to focus on for long-term skin care. And once you start your skin care journey, you can keep coming back to the scan and the progress photos to track the benefits of the skin care treatments over time that are planned specifically for your specific complexion.

Now for the 🆒 stuff. The VISIA scan measured my skin pigmentation, pore size, porphyrins (bacteria lodged in pores 🤢), UV spots, sun damage, texture, and wrinkles. Since I didn’t listen to my mom all through my 20s screaming at me to use sunscreen and keep my face and chest out of the sun, I didn’t start any skin care until my 30s 😲 But even until now, I have been random about it…a facial here, botox there, a laser treatment sometimes. Nothing with a long-term plan based on my skin’s specific needs. So that’s why I’m starting from the beginning again with the VISIA scan so I know exactly what my skin needs and I can track it over time 🙌🏼✨

What showed up for me in the scan as the most important area to focus on first are my pores. The lower the percentage result in the scan, the more you need to focus on that area. The lowest percentage for me was porphyrins…which means I have a shit ton of bacteria lodged in my pores 🤮 So they recommended a medical cleaning facial for me first. So, so surprising! I’ve always just jumped into a laser treatment or dermaplane, etc, not even knowing that a huge improvement for my skin would be to just clean out my pores. That will be my first treatment 🧼

I’m so curious if you relate to this post at all…did you ignore your mom, too 🤦🏼‍♀️ and now you’re in your 30s and 40s wondering what skin care to focus on to reverse some of the damage and take care of it going forward? #sorrymom
